description:
MALE Nuttal's Woodpecker. Photo credit M. Lowenthal. 

My favorite Nuttall's Woodpecker (Dryobates nuttallii) observations showing:
Male Red Crown: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/187417851
Female NO red crown: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/190019468
Feather: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/82616203

Nuttall's Woodpecker (Dryobates nuttallii) is a small woodpecker, 19cm (7.5 inches) long, in the Woodpeckers (Picidae) family. Only the male Nuttall's Woodpecker has red at the back of the crown. White outer tail feathers are sparsely spotted rather than barred. Nasal tufts are white. Compared to Ladder-backed, Nuttal's has more black on face, with black cheeks (Ladder-backed has white cheeks). Nuttal's white bars on back are narrow and stop on upper back (Ladder-backed's white bars on back are a bit wider and extend to nape). Nuttal's Woodpecker habitat is oak woodland foothills and canyons. It prefers less arid habit than Ladder-backed Woodpecker. It is a year round local resident in Monterey County, CA in Coast Live Oak woodland with streams and the Salinas River nearby. Diet is a wide variety of insects, especially beetles, also caterpillars, spiders, ants, and true bugs. It also eats some nuts, seeds, fruits, berries. Despite a close association with oak trees, it only eats a small numbers of acorns.

It is a year round local resident in Monterey County, CA in Coast Live Oak woodland with streams and the Salinas River nearby. Nuttall's Woodpecker (Dryobates nuttallii) Small woodpecker, 19cm (7.5 inches) long, in the Woodpeckers
(Picidae) family. Only the male Nuttall's Woodpecker has red at the back of the crown. White outer tail feathers are sparsely spotted rather than barred. Nasal tufts are white. Compared to Ladder-backed, Nuttal's has more black on face, with black cheeks (Ladder-backed has white cheeks). Nuttal's white bars on back are narrow and stop on upper back (Ladder-backed's white bars on back are a bit wider and extend to nape.
Nuttal's habitat is oak woodland foothills and canyons. It prefers less arid habit than Ladder-backed. It is a year round local resident in Monterey County with in Coast Live Oak woodland with streams and the Salinas River nearby. Diet is mostly insects. It feeds on a wide variety of insects, especially beetles, also caterpillars, spiders, ants, true bugs. Also eats some nuts, seeds, fruits, berries. Despite a close association with oaks, it eats only a small numbers of acorns.

COMPARED TO

Ladder-backed Woodpecker (Dryobates scalaris) is a small woodpecker in the Woodpeckers (Picidae) family that is 18cm (7.25 inches) long and is found in arid habitats. Female has a black crown, male has extensive reddish crown. It is closely related to Nuttall's Woodpecker of the Pacific Coast. Their ranges meet in California foothills and they sometimes interbreed there. Compared to Ladder-backed, Nuttal's has more black on face, with black cheeks (Ladder-backed has white cheeks). Nuttal's white bars on back are narrow and stop on upper back (Ladder-backed's white bars on back are a bit wider and extend to nape. It forages for insects and insect larvae on trees, shrubs, cacti, and sometimes on the ground. It also visits hummingbird feeders for nectar.

Yellow-billed Magpie (Pica nutalli) Endemic in California, U.S. Conservation Status: Vulnerable (VU) (IUCN Red List).
Yellow-billed Magpie is a large bird in the Crows, Jays, and Magpies (Corvidae) family. 
It inhabits the Central Valley and the adjacent chaparral foothills and mountains. Apart from its having a yellow bill and a yellow streak around the eye, it is virtually identical to the black-billed magpie (Pica hudsonia) found in much of the rest of North America.

"Large, striking black-and-white bird; related to crows and jays. Unmistakably long tail and bold pattern, especially visible in flight. Look for bright yellow bill and iridescent blue-green on wings and tail. Limited range in California; does not overlap with Black-billed Magpie. Prefers open areas with scattered trees, especially oaks. Often found in pairs or small family groups foraging on the ground."

Nuttall's Woodpecker (Dryobates nuttallii) is a small woodpecker, 19cm (7.5 inches) long, in the Woodpeckers (Picidae) family. Only the male Nuttall's Woodpecker has red at the back of the crown. White outer tail feathers are sparsely spotted rather than barred. Nasal tufts are white. Compared to Ladder-backed, Nuttal's has more black on face, with black cheeks (Ladder-backed has white cheeks). Nuttal's white bars on back are narrow and stop on upper back (Ladder-backed's white bars on back are a bit wider and extend to nape). Nuttal's Woodpecker habitat is oak woodland foothills and canyons. It prefers less arid habit than Ladder-backed Woodpecker. It is a year round local resident in Monterey County, CA in Coast Live Oak woodland with streams and the Salinas River nearby. Diet is a wide variety of insects, especially beetles, also caterpillars, spiders, ants, and true bugs. It also eats some nuts, seeds, fruits, berries. Despite a close association with oak trees, it only eats a small numbers of acorns.

Nuttall's Woodpecker (Dryobates nuttallii) is a small woodpecker, 19cm (7.5 inches) long, in the Woodpeckers (Picidae) family. Only the male Nuttall's Woodpecker has red at the back of the crown. White outer tail feathers are sparsely spotted rather than barred. Nasal tufts are white. Compared to Ladder-backed, Nuttal's has more black on face, with black cheeks (Ladder-backed has white cheeks). Nuttal's white bars on back are narrow and stop on upper back (Ladder-backed's white bars on back are a bit wider and extend to nape). Nuttal's Woodpecker habitat is oak woodland foothills and canyons. It prefers less arid habit than Ladder-backed Woodpecker. It is a year round local resident in Monterey County, CA in Coast Live Oak woodland with streams and the Salinas River nearby. Diet is a wide variety of insects, especially beetles, also caterpillars, spiders, ants, and true bugs. It also eats some nuts, seeds, fruits, berries. Despite a close association with oak trees, it only eats a small numbers of acorns.
